.TH CATATONIT 1 "2026-05-06" "catatonit 0.2.1" "InterGenOS User Manual"
.SH NAME
catatonit \- brain-dead simple container init
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B catatonit
[\fB\-g\fP] [\fB\-P\fP] \fIcommand\fP [\fIargs...\fP]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBcatatonit\fP is a minimal init process designed to run as PID 1
inside Linux containers. It handles signal forwarding and zombie
process reaping for the container's main process, then exits
cleanly when that process terminates.
.PP
Unlike traditional init systems, catatonit does not perform system
bootstrapping, service management, or any other operations outside
its narrow scope. It is intentionally "brain-dead" to minimize
attack surface and operational complexity inside containers.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-g
Forward signals to the entire process group (not just the direct
child). Useful when the container's main process spawns
subprocesses that need the same signals.
.TP
.B \-P
Pause-container mode. catatonit enters a wait loop without launching
a child process. The container will pause indefinitely; signals
sent to catatonit (PID 1) are consumed and forwarded to the process
group.
.SH EXIT STATUS
catatonit exits with the exit code of the child process it
supervises. In pause mode, it exits when it receives a fatal signal.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/bin/catatonit
The binary itself (statically linked, no shared library dependencies).
.TP
.I /usr/bin/docker-init
.BR /usr/bin/podman-init
Common symlink targets for Docker and Podman runtimes.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR podman (1),
.BR docker (1)
.PP
Project homepage:
.UR https://github.com/openSUSE/catatonit
.UE .
